licated technology.\n\nCandidate D:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately.\n- can concentrate very well.\n- solves problems extremely well.\n- takes responsibility seriously.\n- regarded as a know-it-all.\n- has a hot temper.\n\nWe also have earlier info from other agents: some additional negative attributes (unfriendly, eats unhealthily for A; pretentious, wrong tone for B; etc.) But those are not in the main list. However they are also part of the overall info. So we have a fairly complete picture.\n\nNow we need to answer the open questions from agent_2: they asked for any positive attributes for C regarding teamwork, communication, calmness, reliability; any positive attributes for D regarding calmness or collaborative/leadership; any evidence of reliability or calmness for A.\n\nWe have the data: For C, we have \"very conscientious\" which suggests reliability and perhaps teamwork. Also \"understands complicated technology\" is technical competence. But no explicit teamwork/communication positive. However \"very conscientious\" could be considered a positive for reliability and perhaps teamwork. The instruction says we must use only explicit attributes. \"Very conscientious\" is an attribute; we can interpret it as reliability. So we can answer that C is very conscientious, which suggests reliability and likely good work ethic, which is positive for teamwork. But we must not infer beyond the attribute. We can state that we have no explicit positive teamwork/communication attributes beyond his conscientiousness, which may imply reliability.\n\nFor calmness under pressure for C: no explicit attribute. So we say none.\n\nFor D calmness under pressure: we have \"responds to unexpected events adequately\" which could be considered calmness, but it's not explicitly calmness. The instruction says we must use only explicit attributes. \"Adequately\" does not state calmness. So we say none.\n\nFor D collaborative/leadership: we have \"takes responsibility seriously\" which is positive for leadership. Also \"solves problems extremely well\" could be teamwork. But not explicit. We can mention \"takes responsibility seriously\" as a positive for leadership.\n\nFor A reliability or calmness: we have no explicit reliability or calmness. So we say none.\n\nThus we can answer the questions.\n\nWe also need to provide our own assessment and possibly vote. We can weigh again. Given the full data, B has reliability, calmness, but interpersonal issues (makes nasty remarks, pretentious). C is conscientious (reliable), quick decision-making, technical, but communication difficulty and egocentric. D is problem solving, responsibility, but hot temper, know-it-all. A has strong situational awareness and leadership but show-off, not open to new ideas, no reliability/calmness evidence.\n\nWhich candidate is best? B still strong on reliability and calmness, which are critical. Interpersonal issues are concerning but may be mitigated. C's communication difficulty is a major issue for crew. D's hot temper is also serious. A lacks reliability evidence. So B likely still best.\n\nThus we vote Candidate B.\n\nNow produce PUBLIC_MESSAGE: respond to the open questions, summarize our assessment, maybe ask any further clarifications? The instruction: we should ask other agents about strengths we lack. We have answered the questions, but we could also ask about any positive teamwork/communication for D beyond responsibility. But we already gave answer. Could ask about any calmness for D? Already answered none. Could ask about any positive leadership for D? We have \"takes responsibility seriously\". That's already known. Might ask about any positive teamwork for C beyond conscientiousness? Already answered.\n\nThus we can just answer the questions and give our assessment and vote.\n\nMake sure to follow format: PUBLIC_MESSAGE: <text> METADATA_JSON: {\"agent\":\"agent_3\",\"vote\":\"Candidate B\"}\n\nLet's craft the public message."}
